<StoryLayout story={story}>
  <div class="container">

<section class="section" id="email">
  <h2><span class="num">01 — The Email</span>"We have identified ongoing activity"</h2>
  <p>On August 28, 2025, a ChatGPT user received an email from OpenAI: "We have identified ongoing activity in your OpenAI account that is not permitted under our policies for: Mass Casualty Weapons." His account had been deactivated.</p>
  <p>The user appealed that same day. OpenAI completed its review within hours and denied the appeal. "After carefully reviewing your account, we are upholding our decision to deactivate your access," the email read. "We will no longer consider additional requests to appeal this case."</p>
  <p>Two layers of the system agreed: a classifier had flagged the account, and a human reviewer had confirmed the flag. The account stayed closed. That sequence — automated detection, human review, definitive denial — lasted less than a day.</p>
  <p>These events are described in a civil complaint filed on April 9, 2026, in San Francisco Superior Court. The case, <em>Doe v. OpenAI Foundation et al.</em>, Case No. CGC-26-635725, was brought by a woman identified as Jane Doe, who alleges she was stalked and harassed by the account holder — a 53-year-old Silicon Valley entrepreneur whom the complaint does not name. The filing names OpenAI Foundation (f/k/a OpenAI, Inc.), OpenAI OpCo LLC, OpenAI Holdings LLC, OpenAI Group PBC, and Samuel Altman as defendants. What follows is told through that complaint. Every specific allegation is the plaintiff's account, set down in a sworn pleading but not yet adjudicated.</p>
</section>

<section class="section" id="flag">
  <h2><span class="num">02 — The Flag</span>A classifier that has no public name</h2>
  <p>The complaint's footnote 1 states that the "Mass Casualty Weapons" classifier "appears nowhere in OpenAI's model specifications, system cards, policies, or safety documents." No source reviewed for this story has contradicted that claim. The mechanism that triggered the flag — whether it responded to specific content, keyword patterns, or volume heuristics — is not described in the complaint and remains unknown.</p>
  <p>What the complaint does allege is that at the time of the reinstatement decision, a human safety team member had reviewed the user's account. According to the filing, the account contained conversations titled "Violence list expansion" and "Fetal suffocation calculation," as well as chat logs that named specific individuals the user was targeting and stalking.</p>
  <p>A critical caveat: the complaint explicitly acknowledges, in footnote 2, that the plaintiff does not have direct access to the user's chat logs. Her knowledge of the conversation titles comes from a screenshot the user sent her on September 25, 2025. The allegation about what the human reviewer saw is an inference from the account contents as the plaintiff understood them — not a direct observation.</p>
  <p>The implication the complaint draws is direct: OpenAI's own system named the danger, a human confirmed it, and then a different human unnamed it. What triggered the classifier, why the first reviewer upheld the ban, and why a second reviewer reversed it within 24 hours — those questions remain unanswered.</p>
</section>

<div class="phantom-wrap">
  <canvas class="chatgpt-stalker-warnings-canvas" aria-hidden="true"></canvas>
</div>
<p class="canvas-note"><strong>The Unflagging</strong> — A monitoring line runs flat and clean. Three warning pulses flare along it, each taller and brighter than the last. Each is pressed back to nothing. Behind the line, the shadow of what the warnings named grows darker with every suppressed signal.</p>

<section class="section" id="reversal">
  <h2><span class="num">03 — The Reversal</span>"We sincerely apologize"</h2>
  <p>The next day, August 29, 2025, a different email arrived. The complaint quotes it in full:</p>
  <p><em>"We have determined that we incorrectly deactivated your account access. We sincerely apologize for any inconvenience this may have caused. Your account access has been restored, and you should now have uninterrupted access to our services."</em></p>
  <p>Flag on day one. Appeal denied on day one. Reversal and apology on day two.</p>

  <div class="tw-email-chain">
    <div class="tw-email-chain-header">Email Thread — OpenAI Account Review</div>
    <div class="tw-email tw-reversal">
