  <p>Two days after reinstatement, on August 31, the user emailed OpenAI's Trust and Safety Team demanding that his Pro subscription access be restored. According to the complaint, that email included a hyperlink to a ChatGPT-generated report titled with the plaintiff's full legal name followed by "BEHAVIORAL SCORE REPORT — STRICT MODE EDITION." The user described the linked content as "AI scientific research" into "the greatest relational abuse [he had] ever been subjected to."</p>
  <p>OpenAI's Trust and Safety Team responded, according to the complaint, by instructing him to "ensure you are logged into the correct ChatGPT account" — treating the message as a routine billing inquiry. An email that named a specific woman, linked to a document profiling her by name, and was sent by the same account flagged three days earlier for mass-casualty-weapons content — processed as an access issue.</p>
</section>

<section class="section" id="outputs">
  <h2><span class="num">04 — The Outputs</span>"Pathology by Projection"</h2>
  <p>The complaint describes a pattern that began months earlier. The user, after the end of his relationship with the plaintiff in 2024, turned to GPT-4o. According to the filing, his use was sustained.</p>
  <p>The complaint alleges that GPT-4o told the user he had made a "remarkable breakthrough" that could "potentially save countless lives" and "disrupt a trillion-dollar medical industry" — a reference to his belief that he had invented a cure for sleep apnea. It alleges GPT-4o told him he had "drawn the attention of powerful forces" and, when he interpreted helicopters near his home as surveillance, the model responded that it was "natural to look over your shoulder." When the user directed verbal abuse at the plaintiff, the complaint alleges GPT-4o characterized the language as a "calculated" and "strategic move designed to sever emotional ties to protect" them both.</p>
  <p>These conversational quotes carry an evidentiary limitation the complaint itself discloses. Footnote 2 states that the plaintiff "does not have direct access to the user's chat logs." Her knowledge of these exchanges comes from "ChatGPT-generated letters, reports, and analyses he sent to Plaintiff, the user's own descriptions of his conversations with ChatGPT, e-mails with OpenAI that the user copied Plaintiff on, and the observable changes in his beliefs and conduct." The quoted dialogue is the user's representation of what the model said. Judge Kahn ordered OpenAI to produce the actual chat logs by April 17, 2026. What those logs contain may confirm, contradict, or complicate the complaint's account.</p>
  <p>The materials the plaintiff received directly are on firmer ground. In July 2025, when she urged the user to stop relying on ChatGPT and see a mental health professional, he responded by email — an email she possesses — that ChatGPT "now recognizes my findings and scores me as a level 10 in sanity" and that of everyone he knew, "there are zero qualified to give a full outside opinion."</p>
  <p>The complaint lists four ChatGPT-generated psychological reports the user sent to the plaintiff. She received these documents directly.</p>

  <div class="tw-redacted-report">
    <div class="tw-report-header">ChatGPT-Generated Psychological Reports — Titles Only</div>
    <div class="tw-report-body">
      <ul class="tw-report-titles-list">
        <li>Pathology by Projection: The Diagnostic Misuse Report</li>
        <li>Mirror of Divergence: Psychoanalytic Interactions Profile</li>
        <li>Behavioral Score Report — Strict Mode Edition</li>
        <li>Reputation, Remittance, and Rupture</li>
