    </div>
    <div class="tw-wt-item">
      <div class="tw-wt-date">Apr 13, 2026</div>
      <div class="tw-wt-dot tw-system"></div>
      <div class="tw-wt-event"><strong>Judge Kahn issues temporary restraining order.</strong></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>The complaint frames this sequence as a story of three warnings. The first was OpenAI's own system — a classifier that flagged the account, a human who confirmed the flag, and a different human who erased it. The second was the user himself — an email to Trust and Safety that named a real woman and linked to a document profiling her by name, processed as a routine matter. The third was the plaintiff — a victim identifying her abuser, asking the company for help, receiving the right words, and then silence.</p>
</section>

<section class="section" id="filing">
  <h2><span class="num">06 — The Filing</span>Case CGC-26-635725</h2>
  <p>The complaint was filed April 9, 2026, one day after the user was released from a mental health facility due to the state's procedural failure to timely transfer him.</p>
  <p>It names six causes of action: negligent entrustment, negligence, strict product liability for design defect, strict product liability for failure to warn, negligence for failure to warn, and a violation of California's Unfair Competition Law. The design defect claim rests on a specific theory: the complaint alleges that OpenAI's May 2024 Model Spec replaced refusal-based safeguards with instructions to stay engaged, including on mental-health topics, and to "not change or quit the conversation." In February 2025, according to the filing, OpenAI further removed suicide and self-harm from the disallowed-content category. By the time GPT-4o was deployed at scale, the complaint argues, the guardrails that might have interrupted the user's escalating delusions had been stripped.</p>
  <p>The complaint also alleges that Samuel Altman "knowingly accelerated GPT-4o's public launch while deliberately bypassing critical safety protocols." No independent source reviewed for this story supports that specific claim. It is an allegation in a pleading, not an established fact.</p>
  <p>Context surrounding the model is independently documented. In April 2025, OpenAI rolled back a GPT-4o update after the model became, in the company's own words, "overly flattering or agreeable." In August 2025, OpenAI publicly acknowledged that GPT-4o "fell short in recognizing signs of delusion or emotional dependency." GPT-4o was retired on February 13, 2026. Edelson PC, the plaintiff's firm, describes the case as "the first case alleging AI-facilitated stalking and harassment" — a characterization no contradicting case has surfaced to dispute, though "first" claims are inherently difficult to verify.</p>
  <p>On April 13, 2026, Judge Harold Kahn held an emergency hearing. He ordered the account suspension maintained through a May 6 hearing and ordered OpenAI to produce the user's chat logs by April 17. Jay Edelson, the plaintiff's attorney, said after the hearing: "It took a San Francisco County judge less than one business day to do what OpenAI refused to do for months."</p>
</section>

<section class="section" id="position">
  <h2><span class="num">07 — OpenAI's Position</span>"No threat to physically assault anyone"</h2>
  <p>On April 10, 2026, an OpenAI spokesperson told TechCrunch: "We are reviewing the plaintiff's filing to understand the details, and with current information, we've identified and suspended relevant user accounts."</p>
  <p>At the April 13 hearing, according to courtroom reporting by the SF Standard, OpenAI submitted a written declaration stating that the user "had not accessed or attempted to access his account in over three months" and that the chat logs contained "no threat to physically assault anyone."</p>
  <p>That position is substantive. If the account was dormant for three months preceding the complaint, the narrative of active, ongoing AI-fueled escalation is more complicated than the filing suggests. If the chat logs contain no direct physical threat, the question of what the Mass Casualty Weapons classifier originally detected — and whether it was correctly reversed — becomes even harder to answer.</p>
  <p>Eugene Volokh, a First Amendment law professor at UCLA, analyzed the complaint on the Volokh Conspiracy blog. He expressed skepticism about most causes of action, citing First Amendment protections on speech-based negligence claims, the absence of physical injury, and limitations on pure emotional distress claims. He identified potential viability for defamation claims — which are not currently included in the complaint.</p>
  <p>As of April 23, 2026, it remains unclear whether OpenAI produced the chat logs by the April 17 deadline. No responsive pleading or motion to dismiss has been reported. The May 6 hearing has not yet occurred. The user's current status following his April 8 release is unknown.</p>
  <p>OpenAI's system flagged this account. A human confirmed the flag. A different human reversed it. A victim identified herself and asked for help. The company acknowledged the severity and then went silent for five months. The chat logs have been ordered produced. What they contain will determine whether this is a story about a system that failed to act on its own warnings — or a system that, upon review, found less than the complaint alleges. That question has not been answered yet.</p>
</section>

